messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

- Full HTTP request path:
  /notifications/{notificationId}

- All HTTP methods acceptable: false

- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: false
- PUT: true
- DELETE: true
- PATCH: false

Explanation:
- In NotificationsController.java there are two @RequestMapping annotations for the path "/notifications/{notificationId}":
  - deleteNotification is mapped with method = RequestMethod.DELETE.
  - readNotification is mapped with method = RequestMethod.PUT.
- Those mappings explicitly register only DELETE and PUT for the path, so only PUT and DELETE are accepted by the code.
- There are no @RequestMapping entries for GET, POST, PATCH, HEAD, OPTIONS, or TRACE on this path, so based on the source code alone those methods are not acceptable.
- The class has no class-level @RequestMapping prefix, so the full path is exactly the method-level path shown. (There is an unrelated subscribe endpoint without a method attribute that would accept any HTTP method, but it is at a different path /consumer/subscribe and does not affect /notifications/{notificationId}.)
